CHIKUNGUNYA - TAIPEI EX SINGAPORE
*********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: 25 Nov 2005
From: Kazumasa Matsuki, MD<kmat@mc.rosenet.ne.jp>
Source: China Post [edited]
<http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/detail.asp?ID=96012&GRP=B>

A Taiwanese student who had been studying in Singapore since last year and
who recently returned to his Taipei County home was confirmed yesterday [24
Nov 2006] to have contracted chikungunya fever while in Singapore, a Center
for Disease Control (CDC) official said. The 13 year old student was
detected with high fever at Taiwan Taoyuan International Airport 20 Nov
[2006] upon his return from Singapore. At that time, he said he was
suffering from fever and fatigue, according to Chou Chih-hao, deputy
director general of the CDC under the Cabinet-level Department of Health.
After examining a blood sample from the boy, the CDC announced that the boy
had contracted chikungunya fever -- a viral disease transmitted through
mosquito bites -- making him the 1st confirmed chikungunya fever case in
Taiwan medical history, Chou said.
Chikungunya virus (CHIKV) infection can cause a debilitating illness, most
often characterized by fever, headache, fatigue, nausea, vomiting, muscle
pain, rash, and particularly joint pain, according to Chou. Chou said 3
suspected chikungunya fever cases had been reported in Taiwan in the past,
but all of them later tested negative.
Chou noted that the student's fever has passed and that he is now recovering
at home. Five of his family members have also been examined and monitored,
but none of them has had any symptoms of chikungunya fever, he added.
--
